<doc id="324970" wikidata="Q3980935" url="?curid=324970" title="Tantojutsu">
<text>Tantōjutsu (短刀術) is a Japanese term for a variety of traditional Japanese knife fighting systems that used the tantō (短刀), as a knife or dagger. Historically, many women used a version of the tantō, called the kaiken, for self-defense, but warrior women in pre-modern Japan learned one of the tantōjutsu arts to fight in battle.

==Martial arts that practise tantōjutsu==
Tantō with blunt wooden or plastic blades are used to practice martial arts. Metal blades can be used in more advanced training and in demonstrations. Styles that use tantō:

Budō (Gendai):
* Aikido
* Shorinji Kempo

Bugei:
* Yanagi-ryū Aiki Bugei (Yoshida-ha Shidare Yanagi-ryū)
* Ogawa-ryu Bugei

Bujutsu (Koryū):
* Kashima Shin-ryū (this &quot;ryūha&quot; uses term Kaikenjutsu)
* Takamura-ha Shindo Yoshin-ryu
* Tendō-ryū

==See also==
* Kaiken (dagger)
* Wakizashi

